    "body": "### Problem\n\n`dd` in a buffer with a single line should be equivalent to `S` or `cc` as far as `on_bytes` is concerned since they all result in the same final state.\n\nInstead, `old_end_row` and `new_end_row` are both out of bounds (1 instead of 0), and the byte lengths are also incorrect.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n- create this `minimal.lua`:\n\n```lua\nvim.api.nvim_buf_set_lines(0, 0, -1, false, { \"Hello world\" })\n\nlocal old_end_pos = {}\nlocal new_end_pos = {}\n\nvim.api.nvim_buf_attach(0, false, {\n  on_bytes = function(\n      _,\n      _,\n      _,\n      _,\n      _,\n      _,\n      old_end_row,\n      old_end_col,\n      old_end_byte_len,\n      new_end_row,\n      new_end_col,\n      new_end_byte_len\n  )\n    old_end_pos = {\n      row = old_end_row,\n      col = old_end_col,\n      byte_len = old_end_byte_len,\n    }\n    new_end_pos = {\n      row = new_end_row,\n      col = new_end_col,\n      byte_len = new_end_byte_len,\n    }\n  end\n})\n\nvim.cmd(\"normal dd\")\n\n-- ðŸ’¥ old_end_pos is actually { row = 1, col = 0, byte_len = 12 }\nlocal expected_old_pos = { row = 0, col = 11, byte_len = 11 }\nassert(vim.deep_equal(old_end_pos, expected_old_pos),\n  (\"old_end_pos: %s, expected_old_pos: %s\"):format(\n    vim.inspect(old_end_pos), vim.inspect(expected_old_pos)\n  )\n)\n\n-- ðŸ’¥ new_end_pos is actually { row = 1, col = 0, byte_len = 1 }\nlocal expected_new_pos = { row = 0, col = 0, byte_len = 0 }\nassert(vim.deep_equal(new_end_pos, expected_new_pos),\n  (\"new_end_pos: %s, expected_new_pos: %s\"):format(\n    vim.inspect(new_end_pos), vim.inspect(expected_new_pos)\n  )\n)\n```\n\n- run `nvim --clean -u minimal.lua`\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nAlready described in the problem statement.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.12.0-nightly+19f2e5c\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nN/A\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nmacOS 15.5\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nalacritty 0.15.1 (0c405d5)\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nalacritty\n\n### Installation\n\nNix flake",
